04296nam a22006855i 9780748632404DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222007stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486324047 a10.1515/97807486324042doi  a(DE-B1597)614600  a(OCoLC)1302163243  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPER0040302bisacsh1 aPowell, Anna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeleuze, Altered States and Film /cAnna Powell. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Altered States, Affect and Film -- t1 The Dream Machine -- t2 Pharmacoanalysis -- t3 Altered Body Maps and the Cinematic Sensorium -- t4 Altered States of Time -- tConclusion: Becoming-Fractal -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDeleuze, Altered States and Film offers a typology of altered states, defining dream, hallucination, memory, trance and ecstasy in their cinematic expression. The book presents altered states films as significant neurological, psychological and philosophical experiences. Chapters engage with films that simultaneously present and induce altered consciousness. They consider dream states and the popularisation of alterity in drugs films. The altered bodies of erotic arousal and trance states are explored, using haptics and synaesthesia. Cinematic distortions of space and time as well as new digital and fractal directions are opened up. Anna Powell’s distinctive re-mapping of the film experience as altered state uses a Deleuzian approach to explore how cinema alters us by ‘affective contamination’. Arguing that specific cinematic techniques derange the senses and the mind, she makes an assemblage of philosophy and art, counter-cultural writers and filmmakers to provide insights into the cinematic event as intoxication. The book applies Deleuze, alone and with Guattari, to mainstream films like Donnie Darko as well as arthouse and experimental cinema. Offering innovative readings of ‘classic’ altered states movies such as 2001, Performance and Easy Rider, it includes ‘avant-garde’ and ‘underground’ work. Powell asserts the Deleuzian approach as itself a kind of altered state that explodes habitual ways of thinking and feeling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAltered states of consciousness in motion pictures. 0aAltered states of consciousnessxMotion pictures. 0aAltered states of consciousness. 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074863282440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748632404?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748632404423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748632404/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK